        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 25-year-old female presents to the clinic with a history of recurrent episodes of wheezing, breathlessness, and chest tightness, especially at night. She reports that these symptoms often get worse during spring. Physical examination reveals high-pitched whistling sounds upon auscultation of the chest. She has no significant past medical history and takes no medications. Based on her clinical presentation, which type of hypersensitivity reaction is most likely responsible for her condition?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4804641",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 35005,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. A) &nbsp;Type 1</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Asthma</strong>, particularly <strong>allergic asthma </strong>as suggested by the patient's symptoms <strong>worsening during spring </strong>(allergen exposure), is typically due to a <strong>Type 1 hypersensitivity reaction</strong>. This <strong>reaction is IgE-mediated </strong>and <strong>involves mast cells and basophils</strong>. The patient's clinical presentation with <strong>wheezing, breathlessness</strong>, and <strong>chest tightness</strong>, which are <strong>classic for asthma</strong>, support this diagnosis.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Anaphylactic and atopic—two phases:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Immediate </strong>(minutes): antigen crosslinks preformed IgE on presensitized mast cells→ immediate degranulation release of histamine (a vasoactive amine), tryptase (marker of mast cell activation), and leukotrienes.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Late </strong>(hours): chemokines (attract inflammatory cells, eg, eosinophils) and other mediators from mast cells → inflammation and tissue damage.</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/04/screenshot-2024-03-04-155028.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"532\" height=\"821\"></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/04/screenshot-2024-03-04-155126.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"700\" height=\"690\"></span></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Figure</strong>: Mechanism of type I hypersensitivity reaction.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Type 2</strong>: This <strong>involves IgG or IgM antibodies </strong>directed <strong>against cell surface antigens</strong>, leading to cytotoxicity, commonly seen in conditions like hemolytic anemia.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Type 3</strong>: This involves <strong>immune complex-mediated reactions</strong>, seen in diseases like serum sickness or certain forms of vasculitis.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D. Type 4</strong>: This is a <strong>delayed-type hypersensitivity reaction mediated by T cells</strong>, seen in conditions like contact dermatitis or tuberculin skin test reaction.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:&nbsp;</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/Screenshot%202025-06-27%20165347.png\" width=\"1144\" height=\"678\"></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Ref:&nbsp;</u>Apurba Sastry’s Essentials of Medical Microbiology 1/e p174, 2/e p180</strong></span></p>",
